body.value: It’s no secret that this “winter” has been a bit of a roller coaster ride. In fact, the meteorological whiplash has been so bad in these parts that I swear I saw a Canada goose flying overhead a few days ago wearing a neck brace. I figure he was either looking for someplace with more stable weather or he was in search of the guy who owns sue-annoying-weather-gods.com.

And the weather gyrations haven’t just been local. Two weeks ago I wrote my column from an Augusta, Maine, hotel room where the outside air was so cold the local geese were picketing the L.L. Bean factory in an attempt to get back some of their down feathers. This week I’m writing from Sarasota, Florida, (engaged in entirely work-related pursuits, in case Mr. Tax Man is following along) where flip flops, shorts and a tattered old T-shirt are required writing attire.

But of course, if you and I are not happy with the local weather offering, we have the option of hopping on a cheap flight and going somewhere warmer or colder. Plants, on the other hand, are stuck with whatever comes their way. And this year, it hasn’t been easy. The plants don’t know whether they’re coming or going.

The first thing to understand about plants and weather, at least plants that grow in our neck of the woods, is that they have a built-in dormancy clock. Whether we’re talking about seeds or whole plants, most have a complex internal clock that says, in essence, “sure it may feel nice and warm on this odd February day, but hold your horses, winter’ll be back in a day or two.”
Without that reminder, many of our plants would have pushed out new growth a week or a month ago, only to have it whacked by a sub-freezing “normal” February night.
You may like: Ever wonder how plants handle winter weather like wind chill? The answer? It's about water

But at some point that dormancy clock runs out and lets the plant “know” that the next stretch of nice, warm weather it’ll be time to cut loose and start growing. Now I could spend the next 700 words blathering on about complex biochemistry which, I am certain, would keep riveted all of about three people on the planet. But suffice to say that for many temperate zone plants, such as those we grow in our Kentucky yards and gardens, that dormancy clock sounds its alarm at about 2,000 hours of accumulated temperatures below about 40 degrees Fahrenheit. That equates to about three months of cold.

Now in the perfect world, sometime after Thanksgiving but before Christmas, we’d hit a stretch of 30s and 40s for high temps and 20s at night. After about three months of that perfectly seasonable weather, we’d be past the 2,000-hour mark and plants would be ready to respond to those warm April showers. The problem is, we don’t live in a perfect world, at least not from a weather standpoint.

This past January alone, we had 23 days where the high temperature was above our average range, and we accumulated less than 300 hours below 40 degrees. In an average year, we’d have accumulated closer to 750 hours of cold. February has been just as much of a challenge, which means if we don’t get some more normal winter temperatures we could be looking at some odd horticultural goings-on in the months to come.
The latest forecast: Freezing temps bring chance of snow after Louisville's warm weather comes to an end
Something tells me it won’t be a problem — Mother Nature loves averages.
If this all seems too nebulous to you, here’s a real-world example of how these temperature swings and dormancy clocks can work.

Back in my egghead academic days, I worked on cold tolerance of lowbush blueberry (Vaccinium angustifolium), an amazing little woody groundcover plant that provides all the canned blueberries that show up in your grocery store muffin mixes. We set up a study that involved three winters of sending underpaid graduate students out through the snow on a weekly basis to harvest hundreds of stems, bringing them back to the lab and subjecting them to ridiculously cold temperatures and then determining the temperature below which flower buds were killed.
Read more: Online dating is like dipping your toe into a plant society. Here's how to do it well

The results for the first two years were a big, broad bell curve of low-temperature tolerance starting in November, hitting a peak tolerance of between -22 and -25 degrees from mid-December through about the end of March and gradual loss of cold tolerance after that. And there were not more than a few degrees of change from one week to the next.

But sometimes, good fortune smiles on the scientific method, and in the middle of February of year three, we got the forecast for an insanely warm three days where the high temperatures were to climb over 70 degrees — a full 40 degrees above normal. Knowing that the date of the forecasted warm-up corresponded with an accumulation of just about 2,000 hours of cold, we inserted a couple of new sample dates — one just before and the second just after the big warm-up.
We then threw the lab into 24-hour, blueberry stem-killing mode. The results were pretty startling.

When we compared the data from the immediately pre-warm spell to the immediately post-warm spell, the plants lost a whopping 31 degrees in cold tolerance. That means that plants that were able to withstand -22 degrees on Monday were killed dead as a doornail on Thursday by exposure to +9 degrees.

The next year, we ran the same study but added an artificial warming for 72 hours at each weekly collection date. And while the non-warmed stems out in the field retained their better than -20 degree cold tolerance through much of the winter, come about the third week of February, and corresponding with accumulation of about 2,000 hours of cold, the artificially warmed stems lost a huge amount of cold tolerance.
Score one for the eggheads!

What does this all mean for us this year? Well your guess is as good as mine. But if your bulbs start blooming next week, watch the weather. We might all end up with some large cut flower bouquets on the dining room table
And if you happen to run into that goose with the neck brace, I know a guy.
Yew Dell Botanical Gardens, 6220 Old Lagrange Road, yewdellgardens.org.

WHAT: Join Yew Dell Botanical Gardens executive director, Paul Cappiello, and KAD master distiller Jade Peterson for an informal distillery walk, tasting and a master class in the botany and distilling magic that goes into making bourbon.

COST: $35/$45 Yew Dell members/non-members
MORE INFORMATION: 502-241-4788 or yewdellgardens.org/classes-events/
Garden Designing for the Impulse Buyer

WHAT: We can design and plan all we want when it comes to our garden, but in reality, are we going to stick to it? We’re sure, like us, many of you buy a plant on impulse and purely because you “HAVE to have it!” So, if you are guilty of having a midsummer plant nursery on your driveway from plants you found on sale or at a plant geek conference, then this is the class for you! Join us at Logan Street Market, and we will discuss the basics of garden design and planning in order to make those random plant purchases easier to place in your own garden!
WHERE: Logan Street Market, 1001 Logan St.
WHEN: Feb. 26, 6-7:30 p.m.
COST: $20/$30 Members/Non-members
MORE INFORMATION: 502-241-4788 or yewdellgardens.org/classes-events/

metadata.headline: 'Winter' has been a roller coaster this year. What this meteorological whiplash means

items.brief: This “winter” has been a roller coaster ride. In fact, the meteorological whiplash has been so bad, it's unclear what that means for plants.
items.seotitle: Winter 2020 has caused Kentucky to get meteorological whiplash
